nois Huskies]] 27\u20133.<ref>http://www.gousfbulls.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=7700&ATCLID=204845274</ref>\n\nBoth teams played in their first International Bowl.  South Florida played in their fifth consecutive bowl game.  They were previously  2-2 in bowl games and were coming off a 41\u201314 victory over [[2008 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis]] in the [[2008 St. Petersburg Bowl]].  Northern Illinois made its fourth bowl appearance in six years.  The Huskies were defeated 17\u201310 by [[2008 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team|Louisiana Tech]] in the previous years' [[2008 Independence Bowl|Independence Bowl]].\n\nThe game was the third meeting between the two schools.  In 2001, South Florida's first game as a [[Division I (NCAA)|NCAA Division I-A]] team was at Northern Illinois; NIU won 20\u201317 on a last-second field goal.  One year later, South Florida defeated the Huskies 37\u20136 in Tampa.\n\n==Game summary==\nMike Ford ran for a career-high 207 yards and scored one [[touchdown]], [[B. J. Daniels (American football)|B. J. Daniels]] threw two scoring [[Forward pass|passes]] to A. J. Love, and South Florida beat Northern Illinois 27\u20133 in the International Bowl.  [[Carlton Mitchell]] caught six passes for 94 yards for the Bulls, who won back-to-back bowls for the first time.  South Florida scored 24 unanswered points in the second half after the teams traded [[Field goal (football)|field goal]]s in a dreary first half.<ref>http://sports-ak.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=300022459</ref>\n\nIt's the third straight year a [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] running back has topped 200 yards in the International Bowl. [[Ray Rice]] of Rutgers turned pro after rushing for a game-record 280 yards and four touchdowns in 2007, while Connecticut's [[Donald Brown (American football)|Donald Brown]] ran for 261 yards in last year's game.\n\nNorthern Illinois running back [[Chad Spann]] carried 20 times for 93 yards, giving him 1,038 for the season.  However, the USF defense came up big all day giving up only 238 yards of offense for the game.\n\n===Scoring summary===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Scoring Play\n! Score\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| '''1st quarter'''\n|-\n| USF \u2013 Eric Scwartz 39-yard field goal, 10:17\n| USF 3\u20130\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| '''2nd quarter'''\n|-\n| NIU \u2013 Mike Salerno 21-yard field goal, 13:19\n| TIE 3\u20133\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| '''3rd quarter'''\n|-\n| USF \u2013 Eric Schwartz 19-yard field goal, 10:35\n| USF 6\u20133\n|-\n| USF \u2013 A. J. Love 46 yard Pass From B. J. Daniels (Eric Schwartz PAT), 5:12\n| USF 13\u20133\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| '''4th quarter'''\n|-\n| USF \u2013 A. J. Love 7 yard Pass From B. J. Daniels (Eric Schwartz PAT), 14:55\n| USF 20\u20133\n|-\n| USF \u2013 Mike Ford 24 yard Run (Eric Schwartz PAT), 6:25\n| USF 27\u20133\n|}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:2010 Intl Bowl 1.jpg|Northern Illinois Huskies (in red) vs South Florida Bulls (in white)\nFile:2010 Intl Bowl 2.jpg|Huskies vs Bulls\nFile:2010 Intl Bowl 3.jpg|Huskies vs Bulls\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|2010 International Bowl}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090603200830/http://internationalbowl.com/ Official International Bowl website]\n\n{{2009 bowl game navbox}}\n{{International Bowl navbox}}\n{{Northern Illinois Huskies bowl game navbox}}\n{{South Florida Bulls bowl game navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2009\u201310 NCAA football bowl games|International Bowl]]\n[[Category:International Bowl]]\n[[Category:South Florida Bulls football bowl games]]\n[[Category:Northern Illinois Huskies football bowl games]]\n[[Category:2010 in Canadian sports]]\n[[Category:2010 in Ontario|International Bowl]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_International_Bowl"}
